    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Corzine's Advantage Wasn't Only Money</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>J Philip Zand letter, commenting on June 7 article, says New York State could use the kind of open and hotly contested primaries that New Jersey has</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>While there must be certain relief for New York residents who had to endure the TV ad campaigns of the contenders in the New Jersey primary that the election is over (front page, June 7), it has been refreshing to see candidates in both parties competing for places on the November ballot -- an opportunity rarely available in New York.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>While there must be certain relief for New York residents who had to endure the TV ad campaigns of the contenders in the New Jersey primary that the election is over (front page, June 7), it has been refreshing to see candidates in both parties competing for places on the November ballot -- an opportunity rarely available in New York.</p>
        <p>We are like Eastern Europeans of a decade or more ago peering over the Iron Curtain to admire the exercise of democracy on the other side.</p>
        <p>J. PHILIP ZAND  New Paltz, N.Y., June 7, 2000</p>
      </block>
